{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"dc721210e8a18083","x":-464,"y":-282,"width":664,"height":942,"type":"text","text":"## 1. Preventing the \"Loop of Death\"\n\nIn a standard message queue, if a consumer fails to process a message, the system often puts the message back at the head of the queue to try again. If the message is \"poison\" (e.g., it contains a syntax error or references a deleted ID), the consumer will fail again, retry, fail again, and so on.\n\n- **The DLQ fix:** After a set number of failed attempts (e.g., 3 or 5 retries), the system moves the message to the DLQ, allowing the main queue to continue processing healthy messages.\n    \n\n## 2. Debugging and Forensics\n\nWithout a DLQ, failed messages often just disappear into logs or get deleted.\n\n- **The DLQ fix:** It stores the exact payload of the failed message. As a developer, you can inspect the DLQ to see exactly what data caused the crash, which makes fixing the underlying bug much easier.\n    \n\n## 3. Handling Downstream Outages\n\nSometimes a message isn't \"bad,\" but a downstream service (like a 3rd party Payment Gateway or a Database) is temporarily offline.\n\n- **The DLQ fix:** Messages are parked in the DLQ until the external service is back online. Once the system is healthy, you can **redrive** (re-inject) those messages back into the main queue to be processed normally.\n    \n\n## 4. Protecting System Resources\n\nIf one \"poison message\" causes a service to crash and restart repeatedly, it can consume 100% of your CPU or RAM, affecting every other user.\n\n- **The DLQ fix:** By isolating the problematic message, you ensure the rest of your system remains stable and performant."}
	],
	"edges":[]
